    {
      "id": "sqV5YM6HdzxYEK0Y_J_js",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -170.28330298441998,
      "y": 3803.773613180958,
      "width": 1241.4390869140625,
      "height": 1500,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#e03131",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 1,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b7i",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 2076474040,
      "version": 932,
      "versionNonce": 715447452,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1783244412215,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n1. Workflow Registration\n\n- Maintain an in-memory mapping of Event → Workflow(s) for fast lookup.\n- This mapping is loaded during service startup and refreshed whenever workflow configurations change.\n\n2. Signal Processing\n\nWhen a signal/event is received:\n\n1. Identify the workflows associated with the event using the Event → Workflow mapping.\n2. Perform basic validation on the signal payload.\n3. Create a new workflow run instance.\n4. Mark the workflow run status as RUNNING.\n5. Start workflow execution.\n\n3. Parallel Execution\n\n- Multiple workflow runs can execute simultaneously.\n- To avoid blocking request-processing threads, workflow execution is delegated to an asynchronous execution layer.\n- This enables high throughput and parallel processing of workflow runs.\n\n4. Workflow Status Tracking\n\n- Every workflow state transition is published to a Kafka topic.\n- Message key format:\n    wfId + runId\n- This provides ordering guarantees for updates belonging to the same workflow run and enables auditability.\n\n5. Delay Handling\n\nFor delay steps within a workflow:\n\n1. Store delayed workflow runs in a Redis Sorted Set.\n2. The score represents the workflow’s next execution timestamp.\n3. A scheduler polls Redis every minute and retrieves all entries whose execution time is less than or equal to the current time.\n4. For each eligible entry:\n    - Remove it from the sorted set.\n    - Mark the workflow run as RUNNING.\n    - Resume workflow execution with a flag indicating that the delay condition has been satisfied.\n\nDelay Cancellation\n\nIf a signal/event arrives that satisfies the workflow condition before the delay expires:\n\n1. Remove the workflow run from the Redis Sorted Set.\n2. Mark the delay step as completed or cancelled.\n3. Continue workflow execution without waiting for the scheduled delay.\n\n6. Action Execution\n\nSupported workflow actions include:\n\n- Slack notifications\n    * Channel notifications\n    * Direct messages via Slack bot\n- PagerDuty incident creation/escalation\n- Email notifications\n\n   ",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n1. Workflow Registration\n\n- Maintain an in-memory mapping of Event → Workflow(s) for fast lookup.\n- This mapping is loaded during service startup and refreshed whenever workflow configurations change.\n\n2. Signal Processing\n\nWhen a signal/event is received:\n\n1. Identify the workflows associated with the event using the Event → Workflow mapping.\n2. Perform basic validation on the signal payload.\n3. Create a new workflow run instance.\n4. Mark the workflow run status as RUNNING.\n5. Start workflow execution.\n\n3. Parallel Execution\n\n- Multiple workflow runs can execute simultaneously.\n- To avoid blocking request-processing threads, workflow execution is delegated to an asynchronous execution layer.\n- This enables high throughput and parallel processing of workflow runs.\n\n4. Workflow Status Tracking\n\n- Every workflow state transition is published to a Kafka topic.\n- Message key format:\n    wfId + runId\n- This provides ordering guarantees for updates belonging to the same workflow run and enables auditability.\n\n5. Delay Handling\n\nFor delay steps within a workflow:\n\n1. Store delayed workflow runs in a Redis Sorted Set.\n2. The score represents the workflow’s next execution timestamp.\n3. A scheduler polls Redis every minute and retrieves all entries whose execution time is less than or equal to the current time.\n4. For each eligible entry:\n    - Remove it from the sorted set.\n    - Mark the workflow run as RUNNING.\n    - Resume workflow execution with a flag indicating that the delay condition has been satisfied.\n\nDelay Cancellation\n\nIf a signal/event arrives that satisfies the workflow condition before the delay expires:\n\n1. Remove the workflow run from the Redis Sorted Set.\n2. Mark the delay step as completed or cancelled.\n3. Continue workflow execution without waiting for the scheduled delay.\n\n6. Action Execution\n\nSupported workflow actions include:\n\n- Slack notifications\n    * Channel notifications\n    * Direct messages via Slack bot\n- PagerDuty incident creation/escalation\n- Email notifications\n\n   ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
